arefully consider the reviewer comments, which are attached, and submit a list of responses to the comments.\r\nPlease amend your paper based on the comments. All amendment in the manuscript, please highlight (use Track Changes). Please prepare a separate document titled - Reply to Reviewer(s) comments. In that document, write down the (1) reviewer(s) comment, (2) Author(s) reply to reviewer(s) comment and (3) amendment in the Manuscript (What you added or deleted based on the comments) for Each Comment. Please note thatJEB will not consider your paper further if you do not follow the instructions properly as mentioned above.\r\n\r\nPlease send the amended version of your paper by 15thJuly 2019.\r\n\r\n\r\nReviewer\'s Comments\r\n\r\nAbstract\r\n• Should be precise and explained important findings. The last sentence in abstract section is unclear and not abstract-suitable.\r\n\r\nIntroduction.\r\n• The definition of Organizational Climate (OC) and Organizational Citizenship Behavior (OCB) should be discussed early in this section in order to allow readers understand the content of the paper.\r\n• The used of abbreviated need to be corrected. The ‘OCB’ abbreviation only appear at page 3 while Organizational Citizenship Behavior is written a number of times beginning from page 1. This applies to other abbreviations used in this paper (EI, LMX, ECL and others)\r\n• The flow of writing makes it is difficult to understand because in many parts, the sentences and paragraph are not linked to previous sentence.\r\n\r\nStudy objectives\r\n• Not clear\r\n\r\nTheories Foundations\r\n• The flow of writing makes it is difficult to understand because in many parts, the sentences and paragraph are not linked to previous sentence.\r\n• Para 2, line 4 needs citation.\r\n• How is social intelligence and emotional intelligence similar (Para 2, line 1).\r\n• Para 5, Line 1, LMX is not written full as this is the first time abbreviation is used.\r\n• Para 7 – to reconsider if the para is suitable for theories foundations’ section.\r\n\r\nLiterature Review\r\n• Malaysian Banking Industry – need to include previous literature of Malaysian Banking Industry studies with regard to OCB, OC. For now, the written facts are not Lit Review.\r\n• Lit Review supposed to discussed previous method/operations/ findings of related study. This paper however only provides the definitions of its variables. Non- explained how previous studies used items included in the stated framework. Therefore, how the framework is generated for this study currently have weak foundation.\r\n• How each variable measured is previous studies are not explained?\r\n\r\nFramework development and Hypotheses\r\n• Refer to Literature Review, bullet number 2\r\n• Framework does not include arrow direction of relationship\r\n• Typo for H7\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n• Suggestion to use table in presenting facts of measurement, EI, LMX, OC, OCB\r\n• what is SEA, OEA, ROE, UOE, OCBI, OCBO\r\nFindings and Analysis\r\n• Table 2 – item that shows high correlation need to be justified.\r\n\r\nDiscussion\r\n• The author used this section to do a written version of results that are already presented using tables in previous section. Results is however not discussed in this section as claimed by the subtitle.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n• This is a section where summary of important findings should be written.\r\n\r\nLimitation and Future Research\r\n• What type of bank currently the study used as sample? It is not mentioned in sampling procedure.\r\n\r\nAcknowledgement\r\n• AAMJ? ?', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '2019-06-26 10:25:20', 91, '', '2019/01258A/cameraready_15615159165d12d78c514738.13282560.pdf', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2019-06-26 10:25:31', 91, 11, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '02', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 10, 26, '10.17687/JEB.0701.02'),
(67, 'JEB.2019.07.01.007', 251, 'Embedding Quantitative Techniques into the Standard Operating Procedure for the Hiring of Part-time Student Workers at EDC-UUM', 'embedding quantitative techniques into the standard operating procedure for the hiring of part-time student workers at edc-uum', 'Linear Programming, Standard Operating Procedure, Part time Worker', 'Apart from offering full-time jobs to the deserving local residents, Executive Development Centre (EDC) of University Utara Malaysia does also provide part-time employment opportunities to their own undergraduate students, particularly the students of tourism and hospitality program. Routinely, the students are hired through short interview sessions. However, based on the complaints received, the EDC management realizes that the outcomes from the interviews have not helped them much in selecting the most appropriate candidates to fill the vacancies. This study therefore aimed at proposing an alternate procedure that combines two quantitative techniques (i.e. simple scaling method and 0-1 integer linear programing model), to enable the management to hire and assign the right positions to the candidates, with better justifications. The usage of the procedure was illustrated by identifying six best-possible students for the part-time jobs available in Semester 2, Session 2018/2019. Three 0-1 integer linear programming models, with different objective functions, were formulated and solved with the aid of LINGO Version 12. Each model derived different set of results, and therefore the management could make their final decision by adhering to the results derived from the model that is congruous with their objective. The contributions of the study and indications for future applications are discussed in the conclusion section.\r\n', '', 5, 'ArticleWorkflow/ha-correction', '2019/asrulhery@gmail.com/submission_15583537005ce29724cf78b0.52044117.docx', '2019-05-20 20:46:57', '2019-05-20 20:01:10', '2019-05-20 20:01:47', 