(74, 'JEB.2019.07.01.013', 251, 'Determinants of Sterilization using a Trilemma Policy: A study in Qatar, Kuwait, Indonesia and Japan', 'determinants of sterilization using a trilemma policy: a study in Qatar, Kuwait, Indonesia and Japan', 'Trilemma policy; sterilization; Mundell-Fleming framework; Central Bank reserve; independent monetary policy; exchange rate stability; free capital mobility', 'Trilemma policy refers to a concept of international economics that states it is impossible to gain all three variables at one time, which is also known as Mundell-Fleming framework. The trilemma policies consist of independent monetary policy, exchange rate stability, and free capital mobility. Pursuing any two of the variables will shadow the other one. Sterilization, on the other hand, reflects the policy set by Central Bank to limit the effects of inflow and outflow of capital money supply. Trilemma policy may influence sterilization, proxy by Central Bank Reserve, as the latter depends on the former. This study determined the relationship between trilemma policy and sterilization by placing focus on four nations, namely Qatar, Kuwait, Indonesia and Japan. Monthly data were gathered from 2009 to 2017. At the end of this research, the findings verified if it is “possible or not possible to maintain all the three variables in the trilemma policy to achieve a stable economic condition by way of sterilization.”', '<p>Aizenman, J. (2013). The Impossible Trinity (The Policy Trilemma). <em>The Evidence and Impact of Financial Globalization</em>, (1999), 381&ndash;390. https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-397874-5.00041-5</p>\r\n<p>Aizenman, J., &amp; Ito, H. (2012). Trilemma policy convergence patterns and output volatility. <em>North </em><em>American Journal of Economics and Finance</em>, <em>23</em>(3), 269&ndash;285.</p>\r\n<p>Berkelmans, L., Kelly, G., &amp; Sadeghian, D. (2016). Chinese monetary policy and the banking system. <em>Journal of Asian Economics</em>, <em>46</em>, 38&ndash;55.</p>\r\n<p>Clark, W. R., Hallerberg, M., Keil, M., &amp; Willett, T. D. (2012). Measures of financial openness and interdependence. <em>Journal of Financial Economic Policy</em>, <em>4</em>(1), 58&ndash;75.</p>\r\n<p>Glick, R., &amp; Hutchison, M. (2009). Navigating the trilemma: Capital flows and monetary policy in China. <em>Journal of Asian Economics</em>, <em>20</em>(3), 205&ndash;224.</p>\r\n<p>Khemraj, T., &amp; Pasha, S. (2012). Dual nominal anchors in the Caribbean. <em>Journal of Economic Studies</em>, <em>39</em>(4), 420&ndash;439.</p>\r\n<p>Mandilaras, A. S. (2015). The international policy trilemma in the post-Bretton Woods era. <em>Journal of Macroeconomics</em>, <em>44</em>, 18&ndash;32.</p>\r\n<p>Michael, B., &amp; Apostoloski, N. (2014). The Middle Eastern Wealth Management Industry: Boon or Bust? <em>ZBW - Deutsche Zentralbibliothek f&uuml;r</em>.</p>\r\n<p>Obstfeld, Maurice, Jay C. Shambaugh, and Alan M. Taylor. (2005). The Trilemma in History: Tradeoffs among Exchange Rates, Monetary Policies, and Capital Mobility. <em>Review of Economics and Statistics 87 </em>(August): 423&ndash;38.</p>\r\n<p>Obstfeld, Maurice, Jay C. Shambaugh, and Alan M. Taylor. (2008). Financial Stability, the Trilemma, and International Reserves, <em>NBER Working Paper 14217 </em>(Cambridge, Massachusetts, National Bureau of Economic Research).</p>\r\n<p>Overview of Business in Indonesia. (n.d.). Retrieved from <a href=\"https://aseanup.com/business-indonesia/\">https://aseanup.com/business-indonesia/</a></p>\r\n<p>Qatar: Staff Concluding Statement of the 2016 Article IV Mission (2017). Retrieved from <a href=\"https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2017/01/03/MS010317-Qatar-Staff-Concluding-Statement-of-the-2016-Article-IV-Mission\">https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2017/01/03/MS010317-Qatar-Staff-Concluding-Statement-of-the-2016-Article-IV-Mission</a></p>\r\n<p>Schoenmaker, D. (2011). The financial trilemma. <em>Economics Letters</em>, <em>111</em>(1), 57&ndash;59.</p>\r\n<p>Schoenmaker, D. and A. Siegmann (2012). International Banking and Financial Trilemma Solutions, <em>TI/DSF Discussion Paper</em>, Duisenberg School of Finance, Amsterdam,</p>\r\n<p>Steiner, A. (2013). The accumulation of foreign exchange by central banks: Fear of capital mobility? <em>Journal of Macroeconomics</em>, <em>38</em>(PB), 409&ndash;427.</p>\r\n<p>Steiner, A. (2017). Central banks and macroeconomic policy choices: Relaxing the trilemma. <em>Journal of Banking and Finance</em>, <em>77</em>, 283&ndash;299.</p>\r\n<p>Yusoff, Zetty Zahureen Mohd. (2014), Post-crisis Monetary Response to Surge Capital Inflows: Policy Trilemma and Sterilizations in Emerging Asia. <em>World Review of Business Research</em>, <em>4 </em>(1), 176 &ndash; 193.</p>', 4, 'ArticleWorkflow/qa-publish', '2019/asrulhery@gmail.com/submission_15590504355ced38c3326e54.34950926.docx', '2019-06-26 10:28:53', '2019-05-28 21:33:06', '2019-05-28 21:33:58', '2019-05-28 21:39:22', 91, 91, '2019/01258A/review_15590507595ced3a0701f1c6.97045157.pdf', '', '2019-05-29 08:55:06', 0, '2019-06-02 11:17:48', 69, '2019-06-02 12:15:13', 'Reviewers recommended Minor and recommended different analysis (however didn\'t highlight why that must be, can\'t just recommend something without solid justification).\r\n\r\nThis is a good paper and I recommend accept as it is.', 5, 4, 'Please proceed with minor revisions as recommended by the two reviewers.', 55, '2019-06-02 14:22:24', 69, '2019-06-09 11:58:07', 'Dear Dr. Nur Zahidah Binti Bahrudin \r\n\r\nThis is to inform you that after careful consideration, the editorial team has decided to reconsider your manuscript for publication, should you be prepared to incorporate minor revisions. When preparing your revised manuscript, you are asked to carefully consider the reviewer comments, which are attached, and submit a list of responses to the comments.\r\n\r\nPlease send the amended version of your paper by 15thJune 2019.\r\n\r\nEditorial Note.\r\nPlease amend according to the reviewer\'s recommendation or provide justification otherwise.\r\n\r\nReview Note.\r\n\r\nSuggestion for Methodology and analysis part.\r\n\r\nInstead of using simple multiple linear regression to determine the the determinant, the Generalize method of moment analysis are suggested. Since the data for one country is greater than 50 ( 9 years x 12 months = 108), GMM method suitable to used. Based on GMM, the authors may test for difference GMM and system GMM. Authors also highly suggested to make robustness test like include time dummy to ensure that the result is not influenced by time specific effects.\r\n\r\nIt is an interesting issue to be discussed especially related to economic issues. However, the beginning of the manuscript was not elaborated properly and should be clearly organized from the issue to the objective of the research. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, the author should check the references. Some of the cited references in the text are not included in the reference list.\r\n', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '', '2019-06-26 10:28:58', 91, '', '2019/01258A/cameraready_15615161335d12d865df2f79.83302655.pdf', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2019-06-26 10:29:07', 91, 11, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, '', '05', 0, '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 52, 59, ' 10.17687/JEB.0701.05'),
(75, 'JEB.2019.07.01.014', 251, 'Interest rate transmission in a dual banking system', 'interest rate transmission in a dual banking system', 'interest rate transmission, monetary policy, dual banking system, OMOs, exchange rate, inflation rate, output growth, monetary shocks', 'This paper examines interest rate transmission and its implications for the effectiveness of monetary policy in Malaysia, the first country to have a dual banking system. It investigates the relationship between the Islamic interbank money market rates (IIMMR) and conventional interbank money market rates (CIMMR), targets of open market operations (OMOs) in each sector, and their relationships with the exchange rate, inflation rate and output growth. The study looks at daily and monthly trends from 2001 through to 2017 using basic regressions, followed by Granger causality, ARDL, and VAR models. Empirical evidences show that IIMMR and CIMMR are highly cointegrated in the long run. A two-way causation exists between daily and monthly Islamic and conventional interbank rates. Based on VECMs estimation, IRFs are generated to show the effects of shocks to IIMMR and CIMMR. It proves that CIMMR has strong influences on exchange rate and output growth, while IIMMR has strong influences on inflation rate. The implication of such results to policy is that a possible feedback of transmission will occur from conventional to Islamic banking system. With the IIMMR being more closely linked to inflation, this indicates the validity of IIMMR as a key monetary transmitter that can be used to replace or be used concurrently with CIMMR. Unlike the empirical evidence from previous studies, this study shows clearly that IIMMR is an efficient transmitter of monetary policy through to inflation rate in predicting economic activity in a dual banking system.', '', 4, 'ArticleWorkflow/ha-correction', '2019/asrulhery@gmail.com/submission_15590505595ced393f2629d1.49231915.docx', '2019-05-28 21:38:50', '2019-05-28 21:3